[Student "S"]
{South is to play 6NT. West leads the \HK.

As usual, you have 11 winners; 3 \Ss, 1 \H, 4 \Ds and 3 \Cs. If \Ss split 3-3 dummy's \S6  will become trick #12. If \Ss don't split though, you will have the chance of a squeeze if the defender with long \Ss also has 4 or more \Cs.

For a squeeze to operate you will need to lose one trick and the time to do that is right now. Let West hold the \HK and win his \H continuation with your \HA. 

East discarded a \D on the second \H.

You might as well find out about the \Ss right now. Play the \S A K Q. 

Too bad, West discards a \H on the third round of \Ss.  

East now holds the the only guard in \Ss.

Play the \DA, then \D K Q. 

East will follow to all three \Ds.  

Now for the squeeze. Play dummy's \DJ and discard your \H10.

If East discards the \SJ you will cash dummy's \S6, then win the last 3 \C tricks. 

So East will no doubt throw a \C instead. In which case you win the last 4 \C tricks.

Squeezes are so very satisfying.}
[Play "W"]HK

